<p>
  Let <m>a</m>, <m>h</m>, and <m>k</m> be arbitrary real numbers with <m>a \ne 0</m>, and let <m>f</m> be the function given by the rule <m>f(x) = a(x-h)^2 + k</m>. 
</p>  
              
  <p>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Complete the following sentence to identify familiar type of function <m>f</m> is, along with key information revealed by its algebraic structure.
        </p>
        <p>
          The function <m>f</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>linear</choice>
            <choice>exponential</choice>
            <choice credit="1">quadratic</choice>
            <choice>trigonometric</choice>
            <choice>cubic</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>, and its vertex is located at the point 
          <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice><m>(0, ah^2+k)</m></choice>
            <choice><m>(k, h)</m></choice>
            <choice><m>(-h,k)</m></choice>
            <choice credit="1"><m>(h, k)</m></choice>
            <choice><m>(0,k)</m></choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>.
        </p>  
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Next we use calculus to study some familiar characteristics of <m>f</m> from a different perspective.  To start, treat <m>a</m>, <m>h</m>, and <m>k</m> as constants and determine <m>f'(x)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>f'(x) = </m><mathInput name="fP"/><answer><award><when>
            $fP = 2a(x-h) or $fP = 2ax - 2ah
          </when></award></answer>
        </p>         
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Find and state all critical numbers of <m>f</m>.  (These will depend on at least one of the constants <m>a</m>, <m>h</m>, and <m>k</m>.)  If there is more than one critical number, enter a list of numbers separated by commas.
        </p>
        <p>
          The critical number(s) of <m>f</m> is (are) <m>x = </m><answer>
            h
          </answer>.
        </p>  
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Assume that <m>a \lt 0</m>. Construct a first derivative sign chart for <m>f</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The first derivative sign chart shows that for <m>x \lt h</m>, <m>f'(x)</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>negative</choice>
            <choice credit="1">positive</choice>
            <choice>sometimes negative, sometimes positive</choice>
            <choice>zero</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>, and for <m>x \gt h</m>, <m>f'(x)</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice credit="1">negative</choice>
            <choice>positive</choice>
            <choice>sometimes negative, sometimes positive</choice>
            <choice>zero</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>.
        </p>  
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          From the sign chart in (d), we see that at <m>x = h</m>, <m>f</m> has a <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>point of inflection</choice>
            <choice>global minimum</choice>
            <choice>zero</choice>
            <choice credit="1">global maximum</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>,
          since for <m>x \lt h</m>, <m>f</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>always decreasing</choice>
            <choice credit="1">always increasing</choice>
            <choice>sometimes decreasing, sometimes increasing</choice>
            <choice>constant</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>, and for <m>x \gt h</m>, <m>f'(x)</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice credit="1">always decreasing</choice>
            <choice>always increasing</choice>
            <choice>sometimes decreasing, sometimes increasing</choice>
            <choice>constant</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>.
        </p>  
      </li>  
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine <m>f''(x)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>f''(x) = </m><answer>
            2a
          </answer>
        </p>  
      </li>  
      <li>
        <p>
          Recall that we assumed <m>a \lt 0</m>.  What does the formula for <m>f''(x)</m> tell us about the behavior of <m>f</m>?
        </p>  
        <p>
          Since <m>f''(x)=2a</m> and <m>a \lt 0</m>, we see that <m>f''(x)</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>constant</choice>
            <choice credit="1">always negative</choice>
            <choice>zero</choice>
            <choice>always positive</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>, and therefore the quadratic function <m>f</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>linear</choice>
            <choice credit="1">always concave down</choice>
            <choice>constant</choice>
            <choice>concave up</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>.
        </p>  
      </li>        
      
    </ol>
  </p>
